England":"England","Dethick, Derbyshire, England":"Dethick, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset and Wiltshire): nickname from Middle English <i>thikke</i> ‘thick-set, stout’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Thick was born in 1242, in Dethick, Derbyshire, England, his father, Geoffrey de Thick, was 27 and his mother, Joan Annesley, was 23. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ellen Whittington. He died in 1287, in England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1242–1287":"1242–1287","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1265–1327":"1265–1327","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1219–Female":"1219–Surnud","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","1242":"1242","1260":"1260","1219":"1219","Ashover, Derbyshire, England":"Ashover, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Dethick, Derbyshire, England":"Dethick, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1242–1287":"1242–1287","1246–Female":"1246–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1265–1327":"1265–1327","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1219–Female":"1219–Kuollut","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","1242":"1242","1260":"1260","1219":"1219","Ashover, Derbyshire, England":"Ashover, Derbyshire, England","England":"England","Dethick, Derbyshire, England":"Dethick, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1242–1287":"1242–1287","1246–Female":"1246–Décédée","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1265–1327":"1265–1327","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1219–Female":"1219–Décédée","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","1242":"1242","1260":"1260","1219":"1219","Ashover, Derbyshire, England":"Ashover, Derbyshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Dethick,